    "summary": "The Angolan Civil War lasted from independence in 1975 until 2002, making it one of the longest and most destructive conflicts in African history. The war began immediately after Portugal withdrew from its colony following the Carnation Revolution of 1974, as three rival independence movements — the MPLA (backed by the Soviet Union and Cuba), UNITA (backed by the United States and South Africa), and the FNLA — fought for control of the newly independent state.\n\nThe conflict became deeply embedded in [[event:113|Cold War]] geopolitics. Cuban troops intervened in large numbers in support of the MPLA, which established itself as the government in the capital Luanda. South Africa intervened repeatedly in support of UNITA, fighting a prolonged proxy war in southern Angola that intertwined with the struggle against apartheid in neighboring Namibia and South Africa. The United States provided covert support to UNITA under Jonas Savimbi until Congress restricted involvement, then resumed support in the mid-1980s.\n\nThe Cold War's end did not end the war. Peace agreements in 1991 and 1994 collapsed when UNITA refused to accept electoral defeat. The conflict continued until Savimbi was killed in combat in February 2002, after which a ceasefire was rapidly concluded. The war killed an estimated 500,000 people and displaced approximately four million, leaving Angola with one of the world's worst legacies of landmine contamination despite the country's enormous oil wealth.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angolan_Civil_War",
